Here are super clear real-world examples of each ‚Äî Uber API, SOAP service, and an internal Java API ‚Äî exactly how to say it in an interview.

üöï 1. Real-World Example of a Web API (Uber / Ola / Swiggy API)
Uber API (REST API example)

When you open Uber and request a ride:

App calls GET /drivers/nearby

Server returns JSON with available drivers.

When you book a ride:

App calls POST /rides

Server creates the ride and returns ride ID.

When you track a ride:

App calls GET /rides/{id}/location

This is a REST API because:

JSON format

Uses HTTP verbs (GET/POST)

Stateless

Resource-based URIs

Real world analogy:
Your phone ‚Üí asks Uber server for data ‚Üí gets a JSON response ‚Üí shows it on the app.

üè¶ 2. Real-World Example of a SOAP Web Service (Banking / Insurance / Government)
Example: Bank Fund Transfer SOAP Service

Banks and large enterprises still use SOAP because of strict security.

A SOAP request looks like:

<soap:Envelope>
  <soap:Body>
    <TransferFunds>
      <FromAccount>12345</FromAccount>
      <ToAccount>54321</ToAccount>
      <Amount>5000</Amount>
    </TransferFunds>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>


Every message goes through:

WSDL contract

WS-Security

XML schemas

Why SOAP?

Highly secure

Formal contract

Reliable delivery

Common in Core Banking, Insurance, Government systems (UIDAI, GST)

Real world analogy:
Bank web server only accepts properly formatted SOAP XML with strict validation.

üß© 3. Example of an Internal Java API (Not a Web Service)

This happens inside your application; no network used.

JDBC API (Internal Java API)
Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, "user", "pwd");
PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement("SELECT * FROM employee");
ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery();


Why is this an API?

Provides a set of methods (rules) for your Java program to talk to the database driver.

No HTTP call

No network (unless DB itself is remote)

Another Internal API Example ‚Äî Java Collections API
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
names.add("John");


You call methods ‚Üí Java handles implementation behind the scenes.

Real world analogy:
Your program uses built-in libraries ‚Äî not a remote server.

üî• Final Interview-Friendly Summary

Uber uses a REST API because mobile apps send JSON requests to web servers.
Banks use SOAP services because they need strict XML-based security.
Inside a Java application, APIs like JDBC or Collections allow modules to communicate without using a network.